I'm working on a podcasting plugin, which makes use of the "rss" action result type. This result type is handled by a confluence class called RssResult which looks up the SyndFeed like this:

SyndFeed feed = (SyndFeed) actionInvocation.getStack().findValue("syndFeed");


If there was a RssFeed interface which has a "SyndFeed getSyndFeed()" contract,  then the code could look like this:

SyndFeed feed = null;
Action action = actionInvocation.getAction();
if (action instanceof RssFeed) {
    feed = ((RssFeed) action).getSyndFeed();
}

The main benefit is that the stack doesn't absorb any exceptions - which are filtered out by the "findValue(String)" method on the Stack, as although they are logged they don't make it out to the browser like typical action plugin exceptions. For an example of what Id prefer to see, throw a RuntimeException from the execute() method of an action.

Another benefit is a clearer contract - I had to hack open the RssResult in order to reverse engineer what I needed to do. The fact that I had to implement a getSyndFeed method was not clear from looking at the confluence RSS generators as a template - I would have picked up on a well named interface much quicker.

If you make the interface match the current requirements, finding the usages and refactoring should be trivial.

